======================================================================
CORRECT H=21 STRUCTURAL ANALYSIS (DIRECTED CYCLES)
======================================================================

--- Part 1: Correct α₁ (directed cycle count) vs H ---

  n=5:
    H=15 ← α₁ ∈ [7]
    H=17: NOT ACHIEVED
    H=19: NOT ACHIEVED
    H=21: NOT ACHIEVED
    H=23: NOT ACHIEVED
    H=25: NOT ACHIEVED
    α₁=10: NOT ACHIEVED

  n=6:
    H=15 ← α₁ ∈ [7]
    H=17 ← α₁ ∈ [6, 8]
    H=19 ← α₁ ∈ [9]
    H=21: NOT ACHIEVED
    H=23 ← α₁ ∈ [9, 11]
    H=25 ← α₁ ∈ [12]
    α₁=10 → H ∈ [29]

--- Part 2: n=5 detailed --- 
  Key: 5-element vertex set can have up to 12 directed Hamiltonian cycles
  (actually at most 3 for a tournament on 5 vertices)
  n=5 tournaments by #directed 5-cycles: {0: 480, 1: 360, 2: 144, 3: 40}

--- Part 3: H=7 with correct directed-cycle α₁ ---
  H=7 requires α₁=3, all pairwise intersecting.
  With directed cycles: 3 could be:
    (a) 3 directed 3-cycles (same as vertex-set analysis)
    (b) 2 directed 3-cycles + 1 directed 5-cycle
    (c) 1 directed 3-cycle + 2 directed 5-cycles on same vertex set
    (d) 3 directed 5-cycles on same vertex set

  Case (c) and (d): at n=5, a subtournament has ≤3 directed 5-cycles.
  3 cycles on same 5-element set are all pairwise adjacent (same vertices).
  This gives α₁=3, α₂=0, I=7. BUT:
  If the tournament has ANY 3-cycle, α₁ increases!

  So H=7 requires: 3 directed cycles with NO additional cycles.
  With directed counting: a 5-vertex set with 3 Ham cycles + 0 three-cycles
  would need the tournament to have no cyclic triples.
  NO tournament at n=5 has 0 three-cycles with any 5-cycles!
  (A tournament without 3-cycles is transitive → no odd cycles at all)

--- Part 4: What (α₁_correct, α₂) gives H=21? ---
  Still need 10 = α₁ + 2α₂ + 4α₃ + ...
  Where α₁ now counts DIRECTED cycles.

  INSIGHT: Two directed cycles on the SAME vertex set are always
  adjacent (share all vertices). So they can never be in the same
  independent set. This means the multiplicity d(S) of a vertex set
  S contributes a FACTOR of d(S) to the count of independent sets
  that include exactly one cycle from S.

  In other words: I(Ω, x) = sum over collections of pairwise-disjoint
  vertex sets, product of d(S_i) × x^k where k = number of sets.

  So H = I(Ω,2) = sum_{k≥0} 2^k × Σ_{pairwise-disjoint k-tuples} Π d(S_i)
  = sum_{k≥0} 2^k × β_k
  where β_k = Σ Π d(S_i) over all k-tuples of pairwise-disjoint vertex sets.

  For H=21: 1 + 2β₁ + 4β₂ + ... = 21
  20 = 2β₁ + 4β₂ + ...
  10 = β₁ + 2β₂ + ...

  β₁ = Σ d(S) over all vertex sets S with an odd cycle
  β₂ = Σ_{disjoint pairs (S,T)} d(S)·d(T)

--- Part 5: β₁ distribution ---

  n=5:
    β₁=10: NOT ACHIEVED

  n=6:
    H=19 ← β₁ ∈ [9]
    H=23 ← β₁ ∈ [9, 11]
    H=25 ← β₁ ∈ [12]
    β₁=10 → H ∈ [29]
    β₁=8 → H ∈ [17]
    β₁=9 → H ∈ [19, 23]
    β₁=10 → H ∈ [29]
    β₁=11 → H ∈ [23, 27]
    β₁=12 → H ∈ [25, 29, 33]

